		{
			"uuid": "b9c9e0e8-a898-47b9-99db-235799211134",
			"title": "SYSTEM: Shoulder Button Items",
			"description": "Create a way to use items using the shoulder buttons, even if they are not on the top side. \n\nPlayer can choose up to two items to place on their sides, this gives them the ability to use these even if they are not on the top side.\n\nThere should be a drawback for this, like increasing the cooldown, or energy used for it. \n\nThe reason for this is that some items might have utilities that are more crucial to the player, such as the healing flask item that recovers their health, some players might want to have this item ready to use in a pinch whenever, so they can tie it to one of those buttons, while other players might want to have a weapon like the shotgun or axe, which allows them to stay on the offensive.",
			"category": "babd24c5-1b43-498a-b581-b41a7d513474",
			"steps": []
		},
		{
			"uuid": "cb3f0b8f-c252-49db-af67-db776dfee4c0",
			"title": "LEVEL: Street Level Progression",
			"description": "Extended descriptions:\nEvent 1: Player arrives, camera pans towards bus stop as bus leaves and player is shown behind it.\nEvent 2: Player meets Tough Guy, who asks if they want to partake in the DPS check challenge.",
			"category": "3f3f4d76-287f-4cd5-a3b9-a443e148dbbd",
			"steps": [
				{
					"details": "Event 1: Bus Stop",
					"done": false
				},
				{
					"details": "Event 2: DPS Check",
					"done": false
				}
			]
		},
		{
			"uuid": "7a8ac56b-3da4-4348-847b-5a9f2a6fd0a4",
			"title": "BUG: Camera needs reset in Forest Level",
			"description": "In the Forest level, when the player goes through the tree log bridge and into Oru's shop the camera is changed but it needs to be reset back to normal. ",
			"category": "d1ec75ea-e255-4504-925b-e4f46ae2be0f",
			"steps": []
		},
		{
			"uuid": "596f44d4-a20d-4b60-b55c-e93cea2923d6",
			"title": "Camera System Rehaul",
			"description": "The camera system needs to be more dynamic so that different camera angles can be added easily but have a way to detect when players are exiting the camera angle area. \n\nSome ideas include using a Global script, or at least one that gets instantiated with every level, and that camera handles the resetting of position, proper offsets, and all that.\n\nWhat currently happens:\nCamera change tile can only detetect player in a 1x1 tile, which forces level designers to have to force players into tight spaces to achieve the camera change. Also, to return the original camera position, a second detection area has to be placed next to the one we just added, making the previously mentioned tight space issue worse. Also we manually have to set up the offsets using a camera position value. \n\nThings we want to fix:\n1. Ideally, we can use a trigger of any size and the camera will adapt to the player position accordingly. \n2. \n\nSome ideas on how to fix it:\n- If there is an autoloaded camera manager script, it can also keep track of player elevation to keep the offset correct.\n- Add or edit a collision box for the player that the camera trigger detects. This collision box will ONLY be active when the player is NOT moving, forcing the camera changes to happen exactly on the frame they have landed and stopped moving. ",
			"category": "d2a03b12-ad2e-4671-81d3-48a51ebecbed",
			"steps": []
		},
		{
			"uuid": "6ef61d25-9d82-400d-8ef4-b3673d803073",
			"title": "Ability Display Rehaul",
			"description": "Since the menu is very hard to work with, it would be interesting to see some ways to rehaul it making it better for later mechanics and systems.\n\nOne idea is to replace using the Animation Player to using tweens. This could let us experiments with variables, possibly using a grid container with Empty Control node pivots that can perform the whole animation for it. ",
			"category": "d2a03b12-ad2e-4671-81d3-48a51ebecbed",
			"steps": []
		},
		{
			"uuid": "91cffdf5-bd17-4e06-a863-58173c768675",
			"title": "SYSTEM: Level Data",
			"description": "Each level should have a dictionary of data that they can use to load or unload certain things. \n\nFor example: \nIn the forest level, when a player first plays here, it shows a cutscene going to the start of the level, and it lets the player pick up the axe. \nThe level in this case would store one bool variable set to false for whether it's the players first time in the level, and then when the level loads it sets this variable to true and saves it. Similarly, there would be a bool variable that changes and gets stored when the player picks up the axe. ",
			"category": "babd24c5-1b43-498a-b581-b41a7d513474",
			"steps": []
		},
		{
			"uuid": "d7f3118b-df1e-4f82-99f1-c40f3dd516d1",
			"title": "GAMEPLAY: Color Matching",
			"description": "",
			"category": "471f5549-33af-4f98-8d7b-239df9494dcf",
